 A fleet of strategic bombers is ordered to destroy an enemy military target. It is known that the target has four key parts, and destroying any one of them is sufficient to achieve the objective. To carry out this mission, the constraints are: fuel consumption is limited to 48,000 liters, 48 heavy bombs, and 32 light bombs. When carrying a heavy bomb, each liter of fuel allows the aircraft to fly 2 km; when carrying a light bomb, each liter allows it to fly 3 km. In addition, for each bombing sortie, besides fuel consumption for the round trip (note: when flying empty, each liter of fuel allows flight of 4 km), 100 liters of fuel are consumed each for takeoff and landing. The relevant data is shown in Table 1-17.  

Table 1-17  


<html><body><table><tr><td rowspan="2">Key Part</td><td rowspan="2">Distance from Airbase (km)</td><td colspan="2">Probability of Destruction</td></tr><tr><td>per Heavy Bomb</td><td>per Light Bomb</td></tr><tr><td>1</td><td>450</td><td>0.10</td><td>0.08</td></tr><tr><td>2</td><td>480</td><td>0.20</td><td>0.16</td></tr><tr><td>3</td><td>540</td><td>0.15</td><td>0.12</td></tr><tr><td>4</td><td>600</td><td>0.25</td><td>0.20</td></tr></table></body></html>  

To maximize the probability of destroying the enemy military target, how should the bombing plan be determined?

-------------
【Python Gurobi 代码】:
 ```python
import gurobipy as gp
from gurobipy import GRB
import math

# Data
parts = [1, 2, 3, 4]
distance = {1: 450, 2: 480, 3: 540, 4: 600}

p_heavy = {1: 0.10, 2: 0.20, 3: 0.15, 4: 0.25}
p_light = {1: 0.08, 2: 0.16, 3: 0.12, 4: 0.20}

# Resources
max_fuel = 48000
max_heavy = 48
max_light = 32

# Fuel consumption per bomb (round trip + takeoff/landing)
fuel_heavy = {}
fuel_light = {}
for j in parts:
    d = distance[j]
    fuel_heavy[j] = (3 * d / 4.0) + 200      # d/2 + d/4 + 200
    fuel_light[j] = (7 * d / 12.0) + 200     # d/3 + d/4 + 200

# Objective weights: -ln(1 - p)
w_heavy = {j: -math.log(1 - p_heavy[j]) for j in parts}
w_light = {j: -math.log(1 - p_light[j]) for j in parts}

# Model
model = gp.Model("Strategic_Bombing")

# Decision variables
x = model.addVars(parts, vtype=GRB.INTEGER, name="HeavyBombs", lb=0)
y = model.addVars(parts, vtype=GRB.INTEGER, name="LightBombs", lb=0)

# Constraints
model.addConstr(gp.quicksum(x[j] for j in parts) <= max_heavy, name="HeavyLimit")
model.addConstr(gp.quicksum(y[j] for j in parts) <= max_light, name="LightLimit")

model.addConstr(
    gp.quicksum(fuel_heavy[j] * x[j] + fuel_light[j] * y[j] for j in parts)
    <= max_fuel,
    name="FuelLimit"
)

# Objective: maximize sum of -ln(1-p) contributions
model.setObjective(
    gp.quicksum(w_heavy[j] * x[j] + w_light[j] * y[j] for j in parts),
    GRB.MAXIMIZE
)

# Solve
model.optimize()

# Output results
if model.status == GRB.OPTIMAL:
    print("Optimal Bomb Allocation:")
    for j in parts:
        print(f"Part {j}: Heavy = {int(x[j].x)}, Light = {int(y[j].x)}")
    
    total_fuel = sum(fuel_heavy[j] * x[j].x + fuel_light[j] * y[j].x for j in parts)
    print(f"\nTotal Fuel Used: {total_fuel:.2f} liters")
    
    # Compute final destruction probability
    survival_product = 1.0
    for j in parts:
        survival_part = ((1 - p_heavy[j]) ** int(x[j].x)) * ((1 - p_light[j]) ** int(y[j].x))
        survival_product *= survival_part
    
    destruction_probability = 1 - survival_product
    print(f"Maximum Probability of Destroying Target: {destruction_probability:.6f}")
else:
    print("No optimal solution found.")
```
